INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (12,1,'2026-07-01 15:14:24','2026-07-01 15:14:24','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco laboris nisi ut aliquip ex ea commodo consequat. Duis aute irure dolor in reprehenderit in voluptate velit esse cillum dolore eu fugiat nulla pariatur. Excepteur sint occaecat cupidatat non proident, sunt in culpa qui officia deserunt mollit anim id est laborum.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','what i learned building headless wordpress','','inherit','closed','closed','','5-revision-v1','','','2026-07-01 15:14:24','2026-07-01 15:14:24','',5,'http://localhost:8881/?p=12',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (13,1,'2026-07-01 15:16:33','2026-07-01 15:16:33','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you''ve scrolled through fashion TikTok or K-pop Twitter in the last few years, you''ve probably noticed the same aesthetic popping up everywhere: low-rise jeans, baby tees, chunky sneakers, and butterfly clips. A lot of that resurgence traces straight back to one group — NewJeans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Who Are NewJeans?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Debuting in 2022 under ADOR (a subsidiary of HYBE), NewJeans set themselves apart from the polished, high-concept maximalism that defines a lot of modern K-pop. Instead, their whole visual and sonic identity leaned into something looser, more nostalgic, and unmistakably late ''90s/early 2000s.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Why Y2K, Why Now?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Y2K aesthetic — named for the turn-of-the-millennium period — is defined by a specific mix: mall-culture fashion, early internet visuals, R&amp;B and UK garage-inflected pop, and a general sense of optimistic, slightly chaotic maximalism-meets-minimalism. For a generation that didn''t live through it the first time, it reads as fresh rather than dated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NewJeans leaned into this in a few concrete ways:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Fashion</strong>: denim skirts, cardigans, checkered prints, and accessories like scrunchies and platform sneakers that echo early-2000s teen style</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Sound</strong>: their music draws on Jersey club, UK garage, and R&amp;B — genres that were bubbling in the actual Y2K era but rarely surfaced in mainstream K-pop before them</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Visuals</strong>: music videos and photoshoots often use handheld camera work, film-camera color grading, and school/mall/skate-park settings that mimic how that era was actually documented</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Bigger Trend</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NewJeans didn''t invent Y2K nostalgia — that cycle had already been building in Western fashion and on platforms like Depop and Pinterest. But the group became a major accelerant for it inside K-pop and across a global fanbase, showing that "retro" doesn''t have to mean over-the-top pastiche. It can just mean picking a specific moment in pop culture and rendering it with a lot of care.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you clock it as genuine revival or just savvy trend-timing, it''s hard to deny the effect: two decades after the fact, Y2K is back on the racks — and on the charts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','NewJeans &amp; the Y2K Revival','','publish','open','open','','newjeans-y2k','','','2026-07-03 01:07:54','2026-07-03 01:07:54','',0,'http://localhost:8881/?p=13',0,'post','',0);
