INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (50,1,'2026-07-03 01:07:54','2026-07-03 01:07:54','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you''ve scrolled through fashion TikTok or K-pop Twitter in the last few years, you''ve probably noticed the same aesthetic popping up everywhere: low-rise jeans, baby tees, chunky sneakers, and butterfly clips. A lot of that resurgence traces straight back to one group — NewJeans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Who Are NewJeans?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Debuting in 2022 under ADOR (a subsidiary of HYBE), NewJeans set themselves apart from the polished, high-concept maximalism that defines a lot of modern K-pop. Instead, their whole visual and sonic identity leaned into something looser, more nostalgic, and unmistakably late ''90s/early 2000s.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Why Y2K, Why Now?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Y2K aesthetic — named for the turn-of-the-millennium period — is defined by a specific mix: mall-culture fashion, early internet visuals, R&amp;B and UK garage-inflected pop, and a general sense of optimistic, slightly chaotic maximalism-meets-minimalism. For a generation that didn''t live through it the first time, it reads as fresh rather than dated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NewJeans leaned into this in a few concrete ways:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Fashion</strong>: denim skirts, cardigans, checkered prints, and accessories like scrunchies and platform sneakers that echo early-2000s teen style</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Sound</strong>: their music draws on Jersey club, UK garage, and R&amp;B — genres that were bubbling in the actual Y2K era but rarely surfaced in mainstream K-pop before them</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Visuals</strong>: music videos and photoshoots often use handheld camera work, film-camera color grading, and school/mall/skate-park settings that mimic how that era was actually documented</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Bigger Trend</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NewJeans didn''t invent Y2K nostalgia — that cycle had already been building in Western fashion and on platforms like Depop and Pinterest. But the group became a major accelerant for it inside K-pop and across a global fanbase, showing that "retro" doesn''t have to mean over-the-top pastiche. It can just mean picking a specific moment in pop culture and rendering it with a lot of care.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you clock it as genuine revival or just savvy trend-timing, it''s hard to deny the effect: two decades after the fact, Y2K is back on the racks — and on the charts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','NewJeans &amp; the Y2K Revival','','inherit','closed','closed','','13-revision-v1','','','2026-07-03 01:07:54','2026-07-03 01:07:54','',13,'http://localhost:8881/?p=50',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (52,1,'2026-07-03 01:11:56','2026-07-03 01:11:56','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you''ve been anywhere near K-pop-adjacent or gacha-game corners of the internet in the past couple of weeks, you''ve probably seen the name "Valko" everywhere — and not because players are excited about him anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Who Was Valko?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Valko was set to be the sixth love interest in <em>Love and Deepspace</em>, the hugely popular otome/gacha mobile game from developer Infold Games (Papergames). He was revealed as a tall, golden-eyed werewolf character — complete with wolf ears and tail — and was originally scheduled to launch with the game''s Version 6.0 update on July 9, 2026.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His reveal initially generated a lot of excitement, especially among fans who wanted a new love interest with a more overtly "beast" archetype. But the excitement didn''t last long.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">What Went Wrong</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The controversy unfolded on two fronts:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Promotional messaging.</strong> Some of the marketing copy for Valko used language and imagery that a portion of the Chinese player base felt romanticized concepts like home intrusion and stalking — read by some as uncomfortably close to normalizing invasive, non-consensual scenarios rather than simple werewolf theming.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Historical sensitivity.</strong> Separately, players connected certain in-game asset codes and placeholder data tied to Valko with references to a historically painful and sensitive chapter of the Sino-Japanese conflict. That association proved deeply upsetting to many players and added a much heavier dimension to the backlash than a typical character-design complaint.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The fallout was significant: the developer reportedly lost around a million followers on Chinese social media, fans staged protests outside the company''s Shanghai headquarters, and the game''s roadmap took a direct hit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Global Fanbase Pushed Back Too — Just in the Other Direction</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here''s where it gets messier: while the backlash was concentrated among Chinese players, a large portion of the <em>global</em> fanbase actually liked Valko and didn''t want him cancelled. Petitions calling for his release reportedly gathered more than 80,000 signatures, and the hashtag associated with him trended worldwide on X.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That created a genuine divide in the community — between players who saw the character as harmful and those who felt a vocal segment was dictating content decisions for the entire global playerbase.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Outcome</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On June 30, 2026, Infold Games officially confirmed Valko''s permanent cancellation. In their statement, the company apologized for the distress caused and said the game would not introduce any further new love interests going forward — making the already-released Caleb the final addition to the roster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Why It Resonated Beyond the Game</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What makes this story stick isn''t just "a character got cancelled." It''s a case study in how a single character reveal can surface much bigger tensions: regional versus global audience priorities, how sensitive it can be to gamify serious historical events, and how quickly live-service games can be forced to reverse major content decisions once backlash reaches a critical mass.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For a game built almost entirely around its cast of love interests, permanently freezing the roster is a pretty dramatic move — and it''s likely to shape how <em>Love and Deepspace</em>, and other live-service romance games, approach new character reveals going forward.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Valko and the Love and Deepspace Controversy, Explained','','inherit','closed','closed','','5-revision-v1','','','2026-07-03 01:11:56','2026-07-03 01:11:56','',5,'http://localhost:8881/?p=52',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (53,1,'2026-07-03 01:13:30','2026-07-03 01:13:30','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you''ve been anywhere near K-pop-adjacent or gacha-game corners of the internet in the past couple of weeks, you''ve probably seen the name "Valko" everywhere — and not because players are excited about him anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Who Was Valko?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Valko was set to be the sixth love interest in <em>Love and Deepspace</em>, the hugely popular otome/gacha mobile game from developer Infold Games (Papergames). He was revealed as a tall, golden-eyed werewolf character — complete with wolf ears and tail — and was originally scheduled to launch with the game''s Version 6.0 update on July 9, 2026.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His reveal initially generated a lot of excitement, especially among fans who wanted a new love interest with a more overtly "beast" archetype. But the excitement didn''t last long.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">What Went Wrong</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The controversy unfolded on two fronts:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Promotional messaging.</strong> Some of the marketing copy for Valko used language and imagery that a portion of the Chinese player base felt romanticized concepts like home intrusion and stalking — read by some as uncomfortably close to normalizing invasive, non-consensual scenarios rather than simple werewolf theming.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Historical sensitivity.</strong> Separately, players connected certain in-game asset codes and placeholder data tied to Valko with references to a historically painful and sensitive chapter of the Sino-Japanese conflict. That association proved deeply upsetting to many players and added a much heavier dimension to the backlash than a typical character-design complaint.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The fallout was significant: the developer reportedly lost around a million followers on Chinese social media, fans staged protests outside the company''s Shanghai headquarters, and the game''s roadmap took a direct hit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Global Fanbase Pushed Back Too — Just in the Other Direction</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here''s where it gets messier: while the backlash was concentrated among Chinese players, a large portion of the <em>global</em> fanbase actually liked Valko and didn''t want him cancelled. Petitions calling for his release reportedly gathered more than 80,000 signatures, and the hashtag associated with him trended worldwide on X.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That created a genuine divide in the community — between players who saw the character as harmful and those who felt a vocal segment was dictating content decisions for the entire global playerbase.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Outcome</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On June 30, 2026, Infold Games officially confirmed Valko''s permanent cancellation. In their statement, the company apologized for the distress caused and said the game would not introduce any further new love interests going forward — making the already-released Caleb the final addition to the roster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Why It Resonated Beyond the Game</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What makes this story stick isn''t just "a character got cancelled." It''s a case study in how a single character reveal can surface much bigger tensions: regional versus global audience priorities, how sensitive it can be to gamify serious historical events, and how quickly live-service games can be forced to reverse major content decisions once backlash reaches a critical mass.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For a game built almost entirely around its cast of love interests, permanently freezing the roster is a pretty dramatic move — and it''s likely to shape how <em>Love and Deepspace</em>, and other live-service romance games, approach new character reveals going forward.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Valko and the Love and Deepspace Controversy','','inherit','closed','closed','','5-revision-v1','','','2026-07-03 01:13:30','2026-07-03 01:13:30','',5,'http://localhost:8881/?p=53',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (54,1,'2026-07-03 01:14:18','2026-07-03 01:14:18','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Open TikTok and scroll for a minute, and sooner or later you''ll land on someone crying while hugging a book, or a color-coded bookshelf captioned "the book that changed my life." Welcome to BookTok — the corner of TikTok that, somewhat surprisingly, has gotten a generation supposedly "too online to read" back into bookstores.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">What Is BookTok?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BookTok is a community of readers on TikTok who share recommendations, reviews, and raw emotional reactions to what they''re reading. The videos are usually short, personal, and unpolished — a far cry from the formal, buttoned-up tone of a traditional book review. That informality is exactly why it works: it feels relatable, and relatable is what makes people curious enough to click "buy."</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Why It Actually Moves the Needle on Reading</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A few reasons BookTok has managed to genuinely shift reading habits, especially among teens and young adults:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Recommendations from peers, not critics.</strong> People trust a recommendation from someone who feels like "one of them" far more than a formal review.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>A format built for short attention spans.</strong> A 30-60 second video is easier to sit through than a long-form review, which pulls in people who''d normally skip written criticism entirely.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Genuine emotional reaction.</strong> Crying, gasping, laughing on camera turns a book into an experience rather than just content to consume.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Fast viral snowball effect.</strong> One video can send a book — even one published years earlier — right back onto bestseller lists overnight.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Real-World Effect</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bookstores and online reading platforms have started tagging shelves and categories with labels like "TikTok Made Me Buy It." Local reading communities have grown on the platform too, discussing both translated titles and homegrown authors, often spilling over into discussion on Twitter/X and Instagram.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">It''s Not Without Criticism</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Not everyone''s convinced it''s an unqualified win. Some argue BookTok is better at driving purchases than at getting people to actually finish books, or that the trend tends to spotlight the same handful of genres and titles, narrowing what gets attention rather than broadening it. There''s also concern that some books get pushed mainly for their "aesthetic" or social media shareability rather than the quality of the writing itself.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Takeaway</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pros and cons aside, one thing is clear: BookTok has made reading feel social and exciting again, instead of a quiet, solitary activity. For a generation that grew up on social media, that might be exactly the kind of entry point that gets people back into books.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','BookTok''s Impact on Reading Interest','','inherit','closed','closed','','1-revision-v1','','','2026-07-03 01:14:18','2026-07-03 01:14:18','',1,'http://localhost:8881/?p=54',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (56,1,'2026-07-03 01:31:00','2026-07-03 01:31:00','<!-- wp:group {"metadata":{"patternName":"twentytwentyfive/cta-centered-heading","name":"Centered heading","description":"A hero with a centered heading, paragraph and button.","categories":["call-to-action"]},"align":"full","style":{"spacing":{"padding":{"right":"var:preset|spacing|40","left":"var:preset|spacing|40","top":"var:preset|spacing|70","bottom":"var:preset|spacing|70"},"margin":{"top":"0","bottom":"0"}},"dimensions":{"minHeight":"0vh"}},"layout":{"type":"constrained"}} -->\n<div class="wp-block-group alignfull" style="min-height:0vh;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;padding-top:var(--wp--preset--spacing--70);padding-right:var(--wp--preset--spacing--40);padding-bottom:var(--wp--preset--spacing--70);padding-left:var(--wp--preset--spacing--40)"><!-- wp:group {"style":{"spacing":{"blockGap":"var:preset|spacing|40"}},"layout":{"type":"constrained"}} -->\n<div class="wp-block-group"><!-- wp:heading {"style":{"spacing":{"margin":{"right":"0","left":"0"},"padding":{"right":"0","left":"0"}},"typography":{"textAlign":"center"}},"fontSize":"xx-large"} -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading has-text-align-center has-xx-large-font-size" style="margin-right:0;margin-left:0;padding-right:0;padding-left:0">Tell your story</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {"style":{"typography":{"textAlign":"center"}}} -->\n<p class="has-text-align-center">Like flowers that bloom in unexpected places, every story unfolds with beauty and resilience, revealing hidden wonders.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons {"layout":{"type":"flex","justifyContent":"center"}} -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class="wp-block-button"><a class="wp-block-button__link wp-element-button">Learn more</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {"metadata":{"patternName":"twentytwentyfive/overlapped-images","